<!-- This article was automatically created by [[User:polbot]] from http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B000969. The prose may be stilted, and there may be grammatical and Wikification errors. Please improve in any way you see fit. -->'''Donald Cogley Bruce''' ([[April 27]], [[1921]] - [[August 31]], [[1969]]) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Indiana]].

Born in [[Troutville, Pennsylvania]], Bruce graduated from high school in [[Allentown, Pennsylvania]], and attended Muskingum College in [[New Concord, Ohio]].
He engaged in the radio broadcasting industry, serving as program director, business manager, and general manager from 1941 to 1960.

Bruce was elected as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to the Eighty-seventh and Eighty-eighth Congresses ([[January 3]], [[1961]]-[[January 3]], [[1965]]).
He was not a candidate in 1964 for renomination to the Eighty-ninth Congress, but was an unsuccessful candidate for nomination for [[United States Senator]] in primary election.
<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->On leaving Congress, he helped form the American Conservative Union, a political action group.
<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->Created a management and political consulting firm, Bruce Enterprises in [[Round Hill, Virginia]].
He died in [[Round Hill, Virginia]], [[August 31]], [[1969]].
He was interred in Ebenezer Cemetery near Round Hill.

